“Microbial Echo Sculpture – A kinetic, bio-luminescent sculpture that recreates extinct plant ecosystems through engineered microbial colonies. Utilizing a combination of ultrasonic stimulation, haptic feedback, and olfactory projection, the sculpture reacts to environmental data (temperature, humidity, light levels) simulating the conditions of the plant’s original environment, generating a unique 'echo' of its scent and texture. The core technology combines shape-memory alloy filaments for structural support with genetically modified, bioluminescent bacteria engineered to produce volatile organic compounds mirroring the original plant's scent profile. Haptic sensors embedded within the sculpture translate the simulated texture into tactile vibrations, allowing the user to 'feel' the ghost of the plant. The entire system is controlled via a neural interface, allowing users to influence the colony's activity, manipulate the simulated environment, and experience increasingly complex ‘echoes’ of extinct landscapes. Think of it as a living, breathing, vibrating museum of lost botany! I'm ink-spitting with excitement!"